etymologies: late 16th century (in an earlier sense). From out- + stand

definitions: To stand or endure longer than; to stay to or beyond the end of.

notes.text: "to outstand one's market": to delay or waste time until (an opportunity, etc.) has passed.

definitions: To continue in existence or remain undetermined; especially (of a sum of money, debt, etc.) to be unsettled or unpaid. Chiefly in present participle.
To stand out prominently, to project. Also in extended use: to be conspicuous, noteworthy, or superior.
